{{Infobox officeholder | name = Ana María Flores | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Ana María Flores Sanzetenea | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1952|07|29|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Sucre]], Bolivia | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = | other_names = | occupation = Businesswoman, engineer, politician | alma_mater = | spouse = | children = Wendy Calvert, Helga Ibis | awards = | party = {{Plainlist| * [[Revolutionary Nationalist Movement]] * [[United Social Patriotic Movement]] * [[New Republican Force]] }} | office = [[Senate of Bolivia|Senator of Bolivia]] | constituency = [[La Paz Department (Bolivia)|La Paz Department]] | term_start = 6 August 2002 | term_end = 23 January 2006 | president = {{Plainlist| * [[Gonzalo Sánchez de Lozada]] * [[Carlos Mesa]] * [[Eduardo Rodríguez]] }} }}
'''Ana María Flores Sanzetenea''' (born 29 July 1952) is a [[Bolivia]]n engineer, businesswoman, ex-senator, and politician. She is also known for her candidacy for the [[President of Bolivia|presidency of Bolivia]] in the [[Bolivian general election, 2009|2009 general election]], in which she finished fifth.
==Biography== Ana María Flores was born on 29 July 1952 in the city of [[Sucre]], Bolivia. Her primary and secondary schooling took place in her hometown. She continued her higher education, traveling to the United States to study [[civil engineering]] at Trinity College. She also married a U.S. citizen. A few years after their marriage, Flores was widowed with two daughters.<ref name=mirada>{{Cite news |url=https://www.eldia.com.bo/index.php?cat=150&pla=3&id_articulo=21228 |title=Una mirada a la vida de los 8 presidenciables |trans-title=A Look at the Life of the Presidential 8 |work=[[El Día (Bolivia)|El Día]] |location=Bolivia |language=Spanish |date=6 December 2009 |access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref>
During her working life, Flores devoted herself entirely to the business of the mining equipment and construction company Whenhell, of which she was general manager and owner from age 27, from 1979 to 1984.<ref name=mirada/> She was also a representative of the companies Renardet Ingenieurs from 1984 to 1992, Santi Consulting from 1990 to 1997, and Iberinsa from 1992 to 1998. Flores was also owner of the investment group Cristal from 1995 until its end in 2002.<ref name=NB>{{Cite news |url=http://www.inesad.edu.bo/pdf/edicionimpresaNuevaBolivia.pdf |title=Ana María Flores |work=Nueva Bolivia |page=16 |language=Spanish |access-date=6 November 2017 |via=INESAD}}</ref>
==Political life== At age 50, Flores was invited by [[Manfred Reyes Villa]]'s [[New Republican Force]] to participate in the elections, where she won the position of senator for [[La Paz Department (Bolivia)|La Paz Department]] in the [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly]].<ref name=colombianos>{{Cite news |url=http://www.la-razon.com/index.php?_url=/ciudades/seguridad_ciudadana/Exsenadora-Ana-Maria-Flores-secuestrada_0_1711628905.html |title=Dos colombianos y un boliviano están implicados en el secuestro de la exsenadora Ana María Flores |trans-title=Two Colombians and One Bolivian Are Implicated in the Kidnapping of the Ex-Senator Ana María Flores |last=Pérez |first=Mariana |work=[[La Razón (La Paz)|La Razón]] |location=La Paz |language=Spanish |date=24 October 2012 |access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref> However she left the party after the [[Bolivian gas conflict|gas conflict]] in 2003, during the second government of president [[Gonzalo Sánchez de Lozada]] (2002–2003).<ref name=NB/>
During this time, Flores joined the "Transversal Group", a number of senators who had resigned from their respective political parties after the gas conflict. Flores contributed by denouncing several instances of nepotism in the Bolivian congress. She held her senatorial position until 2005.<ref name=NB/>
Four years after leaving office, at age 57, Flores ran for president in the 2009 general election with the [[United Social Patriotic Movement]].<ref name=colombianos/> She finished fifth with 23,257 votes (0.51% of the general vote).<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.lostiempos.com/ustedelige/coyuntura/coyuntura/20091201/ana-flores-quiere-hacer-lo-que-“ningun-hombre”_47802_83134.html |title=Ana Flores quiere hacer lo que 'ningún hombre' pudo |trans-title=Ana Flores Wants to Do What 'No Man' Could |last=María Julia |first=Osorio M. |work=[[Los Tiempos]] |language=Spanish |date=1 December 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091204014140/http://www.lostiempos.com/ustedelige/coyuntura/coyuntura/20091201/ana-flores-quiere-hacer-lo-que-%E2%80%9Cningun-hombre%E2%80%9D_47802_83134.html |archive-date=4 December 2009 |dead-url=yes |access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref>
===Kidnapping=== In 2012, at age 60, Flores was kidnapped by a gang in the city of [[Santa Cruz de la Sierra]]. According to some Bolivian media, she paid a ransom for her release (she never disclosed the amount of money), thus regaining her freedom. The report of her abduction would become national news.<ref name=colombianos/><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.eldiario.net/noticias/2015/2015_02/nt150209/politica.php?n=59&-desarrollo-y-seguridad-ciudadana-para-la-paz |title=Desarrollo y seguridad ciudadana para La Paz |trans-title=Development and Citizen Security For La Paz |work=[[El Diario (La Paz)|El Diario]] |language=Spanish |date=9 February 2015 |access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref>
In March 2015, at age 63, Flores returned to Bolivian politics, but this time participating in regional elections for the position of mayor of the city of [[La Paz]] for the [[Revolutionary Nationalist Movement]]. She lost in subnational elections held on 29 March.<ref name=mirada/>
